element_texts.text: Completed

Nettie
Elyria
March 18, '63
Elyria, Wednesday, March 18, 1863 --
Dear Isaac,
Here we are all about the little table in the sitting room - baby in the carriage close by me - May & the three boys - It is just after supper time and grandmother is reading to them from Pilgrim's Progress, in which they are much interested She reads half an hour every Evening - We are all doing well baby was not very well yesterday - vomited twice but she fells nicely to day - Charlie wants me to say that he piled up all the wood Charlie Rich saved & split to day - I've just put May to bed - you know she plays come visiting with her babies and knocks for me to notice her - this P.M. she came and knocked on the back of my chair, when I was busy reading & watching baby, and minded nothing about
Completed

her till I suppose she had knocked several times. Finally she raised her voice quite high and, knocking again, said "Knock and it shall be opened unto you, and here I stand knocking" - Dr was up to day & I told him of it and he laughed heartily.  He came up to find the top to his umbrella that Libbie lost off going home from school. She stopped here on the way home.  I showed him your new book on gardening, in which he was interested.  Anna was up yesterday she is very busy getting Hattie ready to go to Ills.  She is going to Cleveland next week stops there a day or two. Sarah Converse goes to Cleveland tomorrow morning not to return here. Mother has got almost a new jacket made for Charlie Rich & it looks nicely.  I went into school yesterday A.M. and heard Weldins class in geog. and the B. class in Arithmetic of Mrs. Parker's, and a class in spelling of Miss Smiths - all did well - I like Mrs Parker.  She seems to understand character pretty well.  Good night - Your Nettie
Completed

Saturday Eve, March 21 - 
1863
My dearest - 
Half past nine, and all are gone to bed but me, and I only linger to write a very little to you.  I wanted a letter from you to night but it did not come - I got one yesterday, written at Indianapolis. We are all well as usual - Little May seems? decidedly gaining.  I do not know as she really needs her medicine - have not sent for it yet. She went over to Mr Mussey's? Thursday morning, with grandmother, and it did her no damage, that we can perceive. Mr & Mrs Parker & Mary D - called here Thursday Eve about nine o'clock (after meeting) to look over our engravings for tableware?
Completed

for exhibition - They took four to Mrs Parker's room to examine and perhaps copy after. Anna thinks Mary D. will hardly be able to walk so far to school next term - the weather being warmer. She thinks she will wish a change on that account. We had a traveller - a man with a big pack on his back Thursday eve, between eight & nine He wanted to sleep in the kitchen We did not know where to send him but Charley Rich waited on him down town, & I guess he got attended too somehow -  Sabbath 22 March - I have been to the AM meeting - grandmother did not want to go - her head ached - so I went with the three boys - John Monteith was there, and listened to an excellent sermon from Mr Wilbur said John, is to preach this evening.  This is a very summer like day.
Completed

The warmest day we have had by considerable - Mr Philemon Bliss was at church - looking pale and thin - do not know when he arrived.  Baby has been vomiting to day again - grandmother thinks it is her teeth.  Mr. Wilburs text - was "Verily, Verily I say unto you They have their reward" - All the reward they wished or would have - praise and applause of men. And this is exhaustive. They have it only for a time.  Then it is gone - and nothing comes in its place.  Monday morn - I expect you will be amused at my letter, for I have written just as I had time, and some with baby in my lap - We had a hard rain all night long with considerable thunder and lightening - It does not rain this morning but looks as if it might. Charlie Rich is going down town
Completed

this morning to get a few potatoes. Mr Waldo had none to spare. Mr Waldo has worked on the manure? part of two days. Our chimney burnt out, with a fury, this morning.  Caught in the furnace pipe first - it was red hot.  I heard John Monteith last eve - Text - salute Tryphene & Triphosa, and the beloved Persis &c? I don't know as I have any of it quite right.  Mr and Mrs Monteith, Senr. are coming to Elyria to live again.  Hope I shall get a letter from you to day - I'll send this by Charlie Rich this morning - Lovingly, Nettie
Completed

Elyria, Tuesday, March 24
1863 - 
My dear Isaac, -
Yours of the 20th with the letter enclosed for Charles R. Metcalf arrived to day - The little boys enjoyed their part - very much - Wilder as much as Charlie perhaps, because he was the big brother, to read it.  We do hope you can return this week but I was saying to mother just now that I would not expect you - The Chicago Draft arrived.  I did as you said with it, and acknowledged the receipt of it to the C. D. Austin who forwarded it. unclear Dr Watt goes to Cleveland Sat. & to Ills next week. Pity they couldn't have gone with you - Rollin too, is going out on business in July - It has been quite warm since the Sabbath, but rained some yesterday morning, and is raining now again.  I am reading as I have time Spencers
Completed

book on education - Rather phlosophical in the beginning, but very pleasant - & useful reading it is, in some things, a book after your own heart. Some ideas about the value of a practical education in place of "dead languages" &c, would suit my father expertly.  Grandmother has finished the jacket - out of the old coat for Charlie Rich. The boy never will know what he owes his grandmother - not so much for patient remodelling of old coats & pants, however, as for higher and nobler good - if he only grows up, Mr. Metcalf--image as doubless he will, a good and true man, Present--image she will feel paid.  In haste your own Nettie M
Nettie Elyria
March 24 63
Completed

My dear Father --
It made me jump to see the nice letter for me from you - Wilder read it to me, and we both kissed little Anna very softly and told her father sent it. She has been a little sick, since you went away. The wind blew very hard this forenoon and when I tried to hold our Christmas Tree, so that Wilder could make it stand up, I could'nt hold it, and had to blow a little ways with it.  It is pretty warm here now. I was so warm, when I came home from churck Sabbath day, that I could'nt keep my coat buttoned and yesterday we sat in the sitting room
Completed

with the door open, a good while.  This afternoon it rains again. One day Old Mary got loose somehow, and went all about the lane and the Biggs lot with her halter dragging, & Mr Waldo cought her and put her in the barn. I wish I was in Ills. with you - I try to help mother. I have piled up a good deal of wood for Charlie Rich, and Wilder & I helped Gertrude set the table. I am trying to learn not to strike anybody. Wilder and I went to Aunty Jenney's to carry a letter and to Aunt Anna's to get a book and the rains cought us and we got our pants wet. ll the flowers are out, but not a great many and some little red berries in the grove, but not very big.  Your little boy, Charlie -
Completed

Saturday Aug 30 1863
Dear Isaac,
I will write a little this morning - for if you do not get unclear to come home to day you will be glad to hear from us and all - Eliab continued to gain, and left by way of Grafton for Sandwich Thursday about half past four. Concluded to give up going to Cincinnati. He could not have gained much strength for he had eaten no solid foods - but said he felt perfectly well - We tried to persuade him to remain till your return. Wednesday A.M about half past eleven the Grafton hack brought our cousin Mary Barber who looks a little like Abby Dickinson, appears very well indeed, and
Completed

will I imagine prove a useful and pleasant member of this family - she is a very desided Baptist Christian.  Brought a letter of introduction from the Lanesville? ministry to our Mr Leonard, and I went there with her yesterday to carry it with her. She seemed quite anxious to see him - but he happened to be out.  We saw Mrs Leonard and, by the way she is very lovely - I had never seen her before.  The children are well as usual. Charlie Rich studies some every day, and cousin Mary is going to help him.  We had a nice rain yesterday P.M and in the night.  Did it make you get cold to be in tents on such a damp night I fear it will. Mr. Waldo fixed the pump
Completed

yesterday, and it does pretty will. Mr Renfield called to see Eliab, about an hour after he left, and yesterday Mr Wilbur called to see him & you, not remembering you were to be away so long.  Dr. De Witt says David Baldwin is home & Dr Gushing - I went to Anna's to supper last night with Mary Barber.  The Catholic School is again opened - cousin Mary sews for me - We shall all be glad enough if you can get home to day.  Loving Nettie - Anna says she is gaining slowly -
Completed

Nettie
Aug. 31 1863
To Camp Cuyahoga Elyria, Monday, Aug. 31 1863
My dearest,
Charlie Rich is reciting his spelling lesson to Mary Barber and baby is asleep - so I'll scribble a little to tell you we are well, and wishing very much for your return I went to my meeting and cousin Mary went to hers yesterday - I gave the library key to Mr Brooks - Dr De Witt told me Mr Brooks seemed a little offended in some way about session room after Mr Johnson had agreed with the Building Com. I hope it is not really so. How did you get along the cold rainy nights we have had?  I was "divided between two" about the nice, big, warm coat you had - I was so glad you had such an article to frighten away the
Completed

rheumatism, and sorry that Eliab had not one just as warm but I hope he has not suffered for lack of it.  Since I began this I've had all sorts of callers, and now must hurry very much to get it ready.  I enclose these circulars - they came last week - did'nt know but you might do something with them where you are. A long letter from Mr Keyes, and two deeds came Friday - favorable unclear them otherwise, I should think, about the mines. If you can look out something for Charlie Rich a jacket I hope you will - And I should be glad if you would think best to get an oil cloth or a carpet suiting your own good taste, for
Completed

our dining room - We do need it. Mr Keyes is going to send you some money right away.  You doubtless know your standing before now in the C.M.? Herbert unclear it to me yesterday.  I hope for a little letter to night, to tell when you are coming - every body asks.  I've had a busy, hurried time since you left - good many callers &c - but get along nicely with it all - Boys have been picking up apples to day C. Rich mowing & unclear in hay - Baby & May just now down to Anna's with cousin Mary - I see Proctor and a team are at work to day on S.Houd? grounds - Mr Parker gone to Camden to Institute - your own Nettie
Completed

Nettie
Dec 4 1863
Elyria, Dec. 11 1863
My dearest,
I received yesterday a remarkably stiff epistle; naetheless it was extremely welcomed. I suppose by now, you are at Du Quoin safe and sound I hope. We are all well as when you left. Charlie & Wilder went this morning to the pasture with the animals without trouble.  The weather is quite mild & unclear. I am going to give baby a ride down to Aunt Anna's this P.M. Grandmother is going down a little while. The plaster is pretty dry in the new room - seems quite firm - floor not yet laid. I am to have the
Completed

a short time this morning - cousin Mary wishes very much she could take Miss Pinney's place.  Yesterday we put the cradle away in Gertrude's bedroom & then showed baby that it was gone - all gone, and she must sleep with mother in the bed. It took me a long time to get her to sleep & she cried a good deal in the night, but I got through with it - hope she may do better to night - I have written this with baby in my arms as you may imagine - but cousin Mary has her now - I went to Anna's with her a little while All are well there -.
Mr Jenkins address is
Capt L. L. Jenkins
16th Reg. Corps d'Afrique
2 Div 13th Army Corps
via N. Orleans - La
Completed

I think Charlie R - will do the best he can with the cow - Little Charlie is coping with toothache again to night - I hardly know what to do with him - Wilder succeeded in going till Thursday night without a check but to day (Friday) he got one. I felt very sorry he did not make out the week - so did he.  I went into his school Wednesday, and talked with Miss Smith about Wilder & feel some better.  I cannot help feeling anxious about Wilder. I hope we may do wisely with our children - I feel like a child myself when I think of training boys and girls to be good & to be useful - God only can make them desire to be truly good.  I must stop - Charlie cries with his tooth, and it is sleepy time for baby  Truly and lovingly your Nettie
Completed

Nettie
Dec 6 1863
Elyria, Dec 6 - 1863
Dear Isaac - 
I am sitting all alone in the dining room.  Baby and Charles sleeping very nicely on the bed in our room - Mother and Charley Rich & Mary as well as Wilder all up stairs,  Baby has slept three nights now, in the bed and done very well. The darling is gaining in health, and consequently in spirit - she is quite lovely. I went this evening to monthly Concert Instead of the old round of "Missionary Intelligence" Mr Wilbur lectured on the first Missionary unclear of St. Paul. There were an unusual number to hear, and it was good. is to be continued Notice to day of "Diner? Circle" at Dr. Strongs next Friday evening. I stopped to Sabbath School to day and, in the
Completed

absence of Mrs Boyd, was urgently requested to hear my old class, and did so.  Quite a full school.  Miss Eliza Wheeler acted in her capacity as Treasurer, it being the 1st Sab? of the month - she will finish up next Sabbath.  I had a letter from Mary Dascomb yesterday - to say she had decided no to come here at present.  In the first place she says Caesar is sold - 2' The roads are dreadful & the way long round by Cleveland. Then there is especial interest in the S.I.? and she is just commencing Music lessons and joining a singing Class - I am very sorry she is not coming - shall write her to reverse the decision.  Mother had a letter from Maria yesterday - All well - Eliab is going to build a ship.
Completed

Monday Many people ask when you will return - It seems to be thought that there is important school matter to come up - I do not know what - cousin Mary has been quite inclined to apply for Miss Penney's place - we have not encouraged it - not knowing what was best about it. Fence about school house grounds is about completed I think - no one has been here to do any work since you left. Mrs Mussey is still quite sick - she had severe dysentery, prostrating her very much.  Mother is here now, but talks some of going back to Anna's in a day or two.  Miss Wheeler has been twice to me to ask me to tell you about some money paid on their slip in unclear that you had not acknowledged - I told
Completed

her you would make it all right when you come.  - Wilders letter came this noon.  He was delighted.  I think he tries to be good, but finds it hard work. May is learning to readfast.  Give love to Mrs Keyes & family. I suppose you will see Mrs Root - before you return.  Very lovingly, your Nettie - May says she wishes she could write a letter, and the beginning of it - be - my dear Father.  I asked Anna if she would send a kiss to papa, and she put up her little mouth at once to kiss, and then said, "Where" in her pretty way.  Here come Wilder from school - without a check - so he has begun the week well.  Charlie Rich is just speaking his 'peice' for examination.  All send love to dear Isaac with ever so many good wishes
Completed

Nettie 
Dec. 10 1863
Elyria, Ohio
Thursday, Dec. 10 - 1863
My own dearest,
The wee ones all in their beds - I sit me down to talk with my pen to you. The children all seem to have severe colds, But are not really sick, and I imagine will not be - I do not see why they take cold so very easily - Baby has not got those eyefour? teeth yet - They have unclear just about through a long time - To day closed the Secondary School. I went in & mother also. Wilder spoke his peice, very well, showing however that he was somewhat frightened. He got no check this week - and he exalts considerably over, thirty anticipated cents. The Calkins trial is over and he is brought in guilty again - and
Completed

is sentenced thirty days in jail and two years in state prison.The relatives feel terribly about it. No body has done a stroke of work here since you left. To day Mr Besis? brought a load of siding, and I think he may come tomorrow and put it on. The bedstead came Tuesday - it looks well.  Mr Wilbur was in school, and Mr. Gates was there, and regretted the absence of the President of the Board and said he would act as Lieut - in your absence - did'nt make so much of a speech as usual.
Messrs Griswold & Trovetts? were there
There seems not to be much to write about The all want to see you a good deal - perhaps none more than that.Grandmother sits here knitting for the S.A.? Fair. Anna is pretty busy at home now, till Libby gets out
Completed

of school, because last Sabbath unclear went home to begin going to school.  The Diner? Circle is to meet at Dr. Strongs tomorrow eve = There is quite a long letter from Mr Jenkins in the Democrat of this week - Mrs Prker called here last night. They leave next Monday for Granville, to spend the whole vacation. I did not mention that Mr Rush was in school and speechified as usual in his soft way to this clear young friends.  Please do you want Charlie Rich to dry up the cow? The feed of now a days increases her milk. Here is Gertrude with a letter from Almeda for mother, and one for me from yourself - just what I wanted - It was written last Monday - and you had no letters from me.  I've sent two, and you
Completed

have one before now, doubtless. We had a laugh over your Irish curato? But you say no word about coming home.  there is a great grandchild at Brownsville for our mother - a little girl, that James thinks is really pretty - born Nov 9. Lissa? writes that the wolves ate up two of their sheep not very far from the barn.  I hope you are well and comfortable to night. image how much I have to be thankful for - If the children are not severely sick this winter, won't it be good. Good night - from your loving Nettie -
Completed

Nettie
May 21 1866
Elyria, Monday, May 21
1866
StLouis
My dear Isaac,
I have had two letters from you to day. One which came to me this morning I suppose must have come Saturday night but I did not hear from the office. It simply told of your safe arrival at St Louis, and of the strawberries.
But to night came a nice long account of your place and your ministers and your impression of the progress of St Louis. during the last fifteen years I think you must rather enjoy noting the change comparing "now and then" as well as meeting some old acquaintances.
I felt a little sorry to have gon away so long; but it will doubtless turn out? all for the best. I shall lose the chance of going with Mrs.?
Completed

Furber as her ticket lasts only through the month of May- She and Percie? arrived Thursday, the 17th. I went down to morning meeting, and then to the funeral at ten o'clock of the daughter of Mrs. bramer (Mrs. Dillon) and then dined at Dr's and went in the P. M. to Mrs Wilburs to sew for her, with some twenty five others and when I got home, about seven, found Mrs Furber & Percie? here- 
She would stop till next Monday or Tuesday for me to go with her but you probably will not be at home before the last of the week. Percie? is quite a nice looking boy- rather small for thirteen. began going to school to day. He is put in the A. class in the Grammar school. 
Mr. Wilbur got home Monday afternoon I think. He came up here Tuesday but I had gone with Anna up to Charles?. We took dinner there & Charles brought us home about four. I saw Mr Wilbur Thursday when I went to sew. He said he did not want anything in particular. came up thinking he might see you. He exchanged last Sabbath with Mr Bosworth of Ridgeville. O dear! The sermon
Completed

seemed like ashes the confusion with Mr. Wilbur's sermons- Mr Wilbur preached in the evening and gave us real food.
"They say" Mr Gaths? did nicely in Sabbath School. Also in the three o'clock meeting of which he took charge. Eliza and Emmeline have just come from the Monday evening meeting- The boys do pretty well though they are very full of play, and of course want to be all the time with Percie?. I think they try to be good. They take good care of the cow, I think.
Anna seems pretty well now. John is fretful on account of his eye teeth I imagine- and the musquitos have specked his face all over with bites. It was very warm yesterday- but is quite cool again to day.
Eliza has been spending the P.M. at Anna's and Percie? went down to supper- Percie? is a firm reader. I love to hear him. Guess he has been in the habit
Completed

of having pretty much everything he wants. drinks coffee & tea unclear-
He seems very careful and steady, and disposed to do right.
All are gone to bed but me. It is past nine, and I think I will go too
Truly and lovingly,
Nettie
-Albina & Charles were here to night all well. Lucy (Eliab's) fell down stairs yester day, and had pain & vomiting and fainting thereafter, at which they were alarmed and sent for Dr. Merat?. But she got over it, and is about as well as ever today_ Anna & Eliza were over there this P.M. Morning meeting suspended since last Saturday. to be recommenced in fall-
Completed

Nettie 
May 24 1866
Elyria May 24- 1866
St Louis
My dearest~
I wonder how you are feeling this glorious morning, Whether weary and loosing all patience with the deliberations, long drawn out, of the very dignified and slow moving body you have written about, or getting used to dullness and so bearing with it better. We were all made glad last night with the nice letters- one for me, one for Wilder & one for Charlie. May expects hers will surely come next. The boys were greatly delighted with theirs. I am glad you are going out to the Iron? mountain.
Almost wish I were with you to go to- This is splendid weather here, and I hope you have as good.
Completed

Mrs Furber spend all the nights here and visits about at her pleasure during days- Percie? took his trunk down to Dr's yesterday and will be there for the present. His mother thinks that the best place for him_ Dr is not well now_was not out at all Sabbath day_ but is better now than then. a sort of billious attack. This has been a week of callers so far. Every afternoon has been quite broken up with them. Mrs. Mussey was in yesterday and Mrs. Swiss. Charles & Albina too with Mr. Kittredge, who arrived yesterday morning and who is on his way out to Iowa to see John and the country_ not in very good health, by the way. looks pale & thin. Mrs Furber and Anna & Charles & Albian and Mr K. went over and took tea at Eliab's yesterday_ Myself was invited but did not dare walk over. I walked
Completed

over Tuesday morning and walked round the grounds, and right home again, and have hardly got over the tired yet. I cannot see why I get so tired walking- This morning we (boys & I) have been working in the "front bed" getting the weeds out and trimming off dead branches and it looks better- but we cannot fasten up the big climbing rose- Mr Ryan hasn't ben here since you left, and O! How the whole garden needs him! Things grow. The cucumbers are up nicely_ I sent a lot of asparagus over to Eliabs yesterday. 
The church is being cleaned. They have a portable stove and heat the water on the spot, and I imagine are doing the job thoroughly-
John has just come running out from the bedroom having had his nap and jumped out of his cradle and safely arrived in the dining room
Completed

without any assistance. He is rosy and well. so is Anna, and I think May is gaining- Emmeline went home yesterday_ thought she should like to say longer, but her mother came for her-
May has cared for John most of the forenoon very nicely.
I do not know if I had better write again or not. This is the third letter I have written- have received three from you
Your own loving
Nettie 
Thursday night.
Just home from meeting which was full & good. Mrs. Furber and Anna D. went with me. Anna stays till Sat. Another letter from you to night mailed Tuesday- I see not why you get no letter from me. I mailed one the second day after you left. Many ask for you. When you will be back
Good night_ Nettie_
Completed

Nettie
May 27 1866
Elyria, May 27- 1866
St Louis
Dear Isaac_ 
I wish you could just look in here to the dining room a minute, and see May and Anna and hear them_ They are trying to sing very zealously "in climbing up Zion's hill"_ It is Sabbath morning and, as it rained hard just at meeting time, Mrs. Furber and I are both at home. Wilder and Charlie & Eliza are gone to meeting- It has stopped raining now but is cloudy- sort of April day- It rained more or less all night_ and all is fresh & bright out of doors. Mrs. Furber thinks to go tomorrow morning.
John is fretful today_ his gums are swelled. Those eye teeth lake their own time to get through- Anna Dascomb?
Completed

went home last night. Dr and Mrs Dascomb? both rode over and took supper with us, and then took Anna back with them. Hattie? and Maria came over last evening to call for the first time since they moved. They seem very happy, and it is really delightful over there; though they are almost out of patience with the tardy workmen- 2 P.M. We have had dinner and May is reading loud to the others, just now they all want to go to the afternoon prayer meeting. The Ladies sewing society meet at Hiram Hall's next Wednesday. The ladies are in a great hurry to get things ready for a strawberry festival.
Anna (sister Anna) is all tired out. The over exertion of all last winter is just showing itself, and she will have to yield herself up to rest and get over it.
Charlie is reading aloud now and Eliza and Wilder have gone to
Completed

three o'clock meeting. I thought perhaps it would do Charlie just as much good to stay and read. 
Eve. 7 o'clock just got John to stay. The dear little fellow_ how can I ever be separated from him- He will do well enough without me, but what can I ever do without him~ To night he came from his play and caught my hand and drew me to the little lounge in our bedroom, and motioned me to sit down on it and then got up himself and put my hand on his shoes. I said "Do you want to go in your cradle?" He at once assented, and showed his delight at being understood. I undressed him & he went right to sleep holding my hand._ A book came several days ago_ do not know whether I ought to do anything with it or no "The Book of Worship" very finely? got up and a pretty good thing, I imagine-
Wilder is just singing "O if my house
Completed

is built- upon a rock". He can really sing considerable-
Eliza si gone to meeting- It still rains gently & steadily- I thought I would not venture, on account of my naughty tooth that ache so hard on the slightest provocation. Mrs. Furber sits here reading the last Independent. Percie? was here to supper- comes in the morning to help his mother away- Mr & Mrs Rollen De Wilt? start on Tuesday- Eliah thinks it very doubtful about his getting away this week or until the very last-
Truly and lovinly
Your own Nettie-
Morning morn- Mrs Furber gone. I went to depot? with her. Dr has gone to Celevand too. Cut the asparagus this morning and sent it over to Eliab's-
Every thing planted is nicely up in the garden. And how this rain makes the weeds grow- One corner of our garden at any rate, might remind one of the "field of the slothful"_ The garden walks are carpeted with an exceeding rich growth of fine green grass that is exquisite in itself~ but rather out of place- Charley Rich? says he might work here some at noon after he gets his job of the curtains through with_
Completed

Pembroke N. YS
Friday, July 20- 1866
Mr dearest~
When I got here I found, to my quiet joy, a nice fat letter from Elvria. a long one from yourself and one from Wilder and Charlie for all of which many thanks,- and to day there came another, mailed last Wednesday- I mailed one to you that same day at Yarmouth.
I feel as if you would not come East this summer- I felt sad at first about it. but the more I think it over, the more foolish it seems for me to wish you to come simply to return with me- I shall get on well enough- I wish I had thought to ask you to send by Samuel the pictures you were thinking to bring- perhaps you will do so- I hope Samuel will return through Elyria- because I want a visit with him- The friends here want pictures of Anna very much, as well as of the others- I had to pay half fare for May from Portland to New Wark?- the first I have paid for her, on the cars
Completed

A sharp eyed conductor came in and, after snapping my ticket, took over to her, and said shortly "How old's your little girl, Madam?" I told him, and he said "half price for her Madam"- so of course I paid it. All were very glad to see us home. Carrie & Frank? are both here- Carrie & Sam and may have been blueberrying to day- They are rather scarce every where this season- May had her pint-cup full of nice ones. She is enjoying the stay here very much. It is a pleasant place to visit. one is so heartily welcomed- It is evening now. nine o'clock I wrote the above just after dinner.
Rev, Mr. Carter and wife were here to tea. He is supplying the pulpit here now. He is a Banger graduate- a very pleasant man indeed. Rev Mr Willy (Goffstown) lives in Pembroke now. third door from here. He and his wife called to see me to night- His little girl has been playing with May considerable to day. He looks nicely. I think he is rather fine looking. He spoke of enjoying your society at Goffstown- would like much to see you to agent for Bible Soc. Stile says they are trying to have an Episcopal chh. at Goffstown
Completed

Have been reading "Ecce Homo" some to day It is very interesting. fascinating style. I wish I had time to read the whole.
Cousin Samuel can get a horde next Monday to take me over to Dunbarton, and cannot get one tomorrow, and they are so anxious to have us stay till Monday that we have concluded to do so, and now it may be that I shall conclude to spend a week from next Sabbath at Dunbarton- not go back to Yarmouth till a week from next Monday. The Dunbanton people want me to spend one Sabbath there, I shall not quite decide about it till I get there. Hope your next letters will be directed to Dunbarton.
Sat morn, July 21
I intended to copy this pencilling but I must write to George this morning & I think I'll send this just as I have jotted it down in odd minutes hoping you will excuse it-This is a lovely morning- The weather has been delightfully cool ever time we came here. People are haying all about. Only about half a crop.
It would be very nice to go home when Samuel Furber goes only I expect it will be later than I shall want to be about getting home- I want to see you all
Completed

more and more. Dont think I can stay very great while more
Tell Wilder May was greatly pleased with her letter. She will answer it soon. O I can not tell anything about how much I should like to get little Anna & John in my arms. To say, nothing of the others-
Mr Willy has just come from Dartmouth commons? to. Had an interesting time; but he said not one other of his class was there, and there were over forty of them I think.
Loving by your 
Nettie-
I am afraid you will be all tired out with the care and keeping awake at night. It seems as if I ought to be there-
